variable defined: TO_JS_SELECTOR=!-function getIdForFirstFormElementWithValue(v){var inputs,index;inputs=document.getElementsByTagName('input');for(index=0;index < inputs.length;++index){if((inputs[index].value.trim()==v)&&(inputs[index].type!='hidden'))return inputs[index].id}return null}function getSubSelector(s){return s.substring(s.indexOf("=")+1).trim()}function idToCssIdSelector(id){return("#"+id)}function toCssSelector(s){var ret=s;if(s.indexOf("value=")==0){ret=getSubSelector(s);ret=getIdForFirstFormElementWithValue(ret);ret=idToCssIdSelector(ret)}else if(s.indexOf("id=")==0){ret=getSubSelector(s);ret=idToCssIdSelector(ret)}return ret}function toJsSelector(s){var ret=s;if(ret!=="%%skip%%"){if(ret.indexOf("#")!=-1){ret=ret.replace(/\.|\\\./g,"\\\\\.");ret=ret.replace(/\/|\\\//g,"\\\\\/");ret=ret.replace(/\\ |\\\\ /g,"\\\\ ");ret=ret.replace(/(\5b *|\[ *)(?= *\d+[^\w])/g,"\\\\[");ret=ret.split("").reverse().join("");ret=ret.replace(/(d\5 *|\] *)(?= *\d+[^\w])/g,"]\\\\");ret=ret.split("").reverse().join("");ret=ret.replace(/\2e\s/g,"\\\\\.")}}return ret}toJsSelector("@itpSelector")-!

Included page: .CommonRoot.ScenarioInclude (edit)

  • Expand
  • Collapse

Root Commons

***** Nomenclature *****

  • Element—Any page element.
  • Selector—The CSS path that can be used to locate any page element. Although other locators can be used, the ITP emphasizes the use of CSS to locate elements because it is easy to specify, fast, and flexible.
  • Text—The content of an element. Either the innerText (Mozilla-like browsers) or the innerText (IE-like browsers) of the element.
  • Field—Any element into which a value can be placed at runtime. Typically part of a form.
  • Value—The value of a field. For dropdowns, it is the value attribute of an option (as opposed to the visible label). For textboxes, it is synonymous with text. For checkboxes/radiobuttons, the value will be on or off depending on whether the element is checked or not.
  • Label—For dropdowns, the visible text for an option (as opposed to the value).
  • Symbol—Used by FitNesse to store values for later use.

***** Base javascript commons *****

scenario toJsSelector itpSelector
$toJsSelector= is storeEval on function getIdForFirstFormElementWithValue(v){var inputs,index;inputs=document.getElementsByTagName('input');for(index=0;index < inputs.length;++index){if((inputs[index].value.trim()==v)&&(inputs[index].type!='hidden'))return inputs[index].id}return null}function getSubSelector(s){return s.substring(s.indexOf("=")+1).trim()}function idToCssIdSelector(id){return("#"+id)}function toCssSelector(s){var ret=s;if(s.indexOf("value=")==0){ret=getSubSelector(s);ret=getIdForFirstFormElementWithValue(ret);ret=idToCssIdSelector(ret)}else if(s.indexOf("id=")==0){ret=getSubSelector(s);ret=idToCssIdSelector(ret)}return ret}function toJsSelector(s){var ret=s;if(ret!=="%%skip%%"){if(ret.indexOf("#")!=-1){ret=ret.replace(/\.|\\\./g,"\\\\\.");ret=ret.replace(/\/|\\\//g,"\\\\\/");ret=ret.replace(/\\ |\\\\ /g,"\\\\ ");ret=ret.replace(/(\5b *|\[ *)(?= *\d+[^\w])/g,"\\\\[");ret=ret.split("").reverse().join("");ret=ret.replace(/(d\5 *|\] *)(?= *\d+[^\w])/g,"]\\\\");ret=ret.split("").reverse().join("");ret=ret.replace(/\2e\s/g,"\\\\\.")}}return ret}toJsSelector("@itpSelector")

Click Action commons 

IMPORTANT! The click any element commons will click an element whether it is visible or not. This is very important for modern UIs, where menu items, and other elements that must be clicked, may not be visible.

NOTE: All of the select commons below take an optionLocator. From the Selenium documentation:


Option locators provide different ways of specifying options of an HTML Select element (e.g. for selecting a specific option, or for asserting that the selected option satisfies a specification). There are several forms of option locators. 
    
      
  • label=labelPattern: matches options based on their labels, i.e. the visible text. (This is the default.)   
      
      
    • label=regexp:^[Oo]ther
      • 
  
    
  
    • 
      
  • value=valuePattern: matches options based on their values. 
      
      
    • value=other
      • 
  
    
  
    • 
      
  • id=id: matches options based on their ids. 
      
      
    • id=option1
      • 
  
    
  
    • 
      
  • index=index: matches an option based on its index (offset from zero). 
      
      
    • index=2
      • 
  
    
  
    • 
  

  
If no option locator prefix is provided, the default behavior is to match on label.



scenario select optionLocator in dropdown withSelector
toJsSelector @withSelector
ensure do runScript on function getElement(s){if(s.startsWith("value=")){return(window.document.querySelector("[value="+"'"+s.substring("value=".length,s.length)+"']"))}else if(s.startsWith("id=")){return(window.document.querySelector("[id="+"'"+s.substring("id=".length,s.length)+"']"))}else{return(window.document.querySelector(s))}} function getSelectOptionIndex(el,optionLocator){var index=-1;var ol=optionLocator.trim();if(ol.indexOf("index")==0){index=ol.substring(ol.indexOf("=")+1).trim()}else if(ol.indexOf("value")==0){var v=ol.substring(ol.indexOf("=")+1).trim();for(var i=0;i < el.options.length;i++){if(el.options[i].value===v){index=i;break}}}else{for(var i=0;i < el.options.length;i++){if(el.options[i].label===optionLocator){index=i;break}}}return(index)} function fireEvent(el,event){if("createEvent"in window.document){var evt=window.document.createEvent("HTMLEvents");evt.initEvent(event,false,true);el.dispatchEvent(evt)}else el.fireEvent("on"+event)} if("@optionLocator"!=="%%skip%%"){var el=getElement("$toJsSelector");el.selectedIndex=getSelectOptionIndex(el,"@optionLocator");fireEvent(el,"change")}

Because ITP commons use Javascript, they require that periods in selectors are prefixed with a double backslash (\\). Ordinarily, only a single backslash is required. 
  
  
  !| scenario | toCssSelector | itpSelector |
  | $toCssSelector= | is | storeEval | on | {function getIdForFirstFormElementWithValue(v) {var inputs, index;inputs = document.getElementsByTagName('input');for (index = 0; index < inputs.length; ++index) {if ((inputs[index].value.trim() == v) && (inputs[index].type != 'hidden')) return inputs[index].id;}return null;}function getSubSelector(s) {return s.substring(s.indexOf("=") + 1).trim();}function idToCssIdSelector(id) {return ("#" + id);}function toCssSelector(s) {var ret = s;if (s.indexOf("value=") == 0) {ret = getSubSelector(s);ret = getIdForFirstFormElementWithValue(ret);ret = idToCssIdSelector(ret);} else if (s.indexOf("id=") == 0) {ret = getSubSelector(s);ret = idToCssIdSelector(ret);}return ret;} toCssSelector("@itpSelector");} |
  


IMPORTANT! It was necessary to create this Javascript-based method because, surprisingly, Selenium does not have a method for checking/unchecking checkbox/radio button fields based on the value of a parameter. Instead, Selenium simply has check and uncheck commands that take no parameters. Furthermore, in spite of the fact that the Selenium reference implies that you can use the type command for this purpose, you can't. This simple Javascript will check the specified check/radio if the specified value is check. Otherwise it will uncheck it.


scenario set check withSelector to checkOrUncheck
toJsSelector @withSelector

Save table value - in return column - for specified row with matching column 

IMPORTANT! On 10/20/16 I parenthesized the Xpath expression up to the [@{rowNum}] clause. I did that because of an obscure Xpath rule 
that requires those parentheses for multiple predicates, but only where the nodeset returned by the prior predicate returns nodes that do not have a common parent. 
This issue occured for the Andover worksheet screen. I applied the same correction to all of the table commons that select rows using multiple predicates.

NOTE: The | switch to main window | and | switch to main window and wait | scenarios are used to quickly switch back to the main window in order to avoid the "Confirm Resubmission Error" that occurs when opening a pdf in a new tab in a chrome selenium browser.  In order to fix this issue using these scenarios, remove the and wait modifier from the click statment that opens the pdf in the new tab (so the selenium browser won't wait for the pdf tab to load), then insert one of the folowing | switch to main window ... | statements just after the click statement.  Also, if necessary to pass a value to the seconds parameter within one of the statements, the value should be one of the following listed: [5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30].

Frame commons 

NOTE: Selenium's frame support is fairly crude and has several undocumented limitations. It appears that most 
Selenium locators are in relationship to the "active document" which, by default, is owned by the top window. In order
to locate elements within a frame document, that frame must be selected first using the Selenium 
selectFrame command, which is described in the `selectFrame` section of 
http://seleniumrecipes.com/content/selenium-command-reference. However, note the following:

    
      
  • Contrary to the documentation, it appears that a frame can only be located by ID, name, or index. Location using the DOM, CSS, or XPath syntax simply doesn't seem to work.
    • 
      
  • Frame location is always relative to the _active document_. This means that it simply not possible to select a granchild frame from the parent frame; you must first select the child frame from the parent frame. Likewise, in order to select the sibling of a frame, you must first select the parent frame, and then select the sibling.
    • 
  

  
Because Selenium frame support is limited, ITAP frame support is also quite limited. Currently, you can select the 
top frame, a child frame, or a grandchild frame, and only ID-based locators are supported. 
selectChildFrame and selectChildFrame | andThenGrandchildFrame automatically start 
from the top frame, so you don't need to worry about where you are in the frame "tree"  when calling these scenarios. 

Finally, since the majority of commons scenarios are Javascript-based, and the Javascript-based methods for locating 
elements within frames have none of the Selenium limitations, these limitations only effect the few scenarios that 
must use the native Selenium commands (such as `SendKeys`).

ensure do runScript on {{function getElement(s){if(s.startsWith("value=")){return(window.document.querySelector("[value="+"'"+s.substring("value=".length,s.length)+"']"))}else if(s.startsWith("id=")){return(window.document.querySelector("[id="+"'"+s.substring("id=".length,s.length)+"']"))}else{return(window.document.querySelector(s))}}} {var el=getElement("$toJsSelector");el.removeAttribute("target");el.setAttribute("download","")}}

Scenario prep download link at Xpath itpXpath
toJsXpath @itpXpath
ensure do runScript on {{function ParsedSelector(s){this.context=null;this.path=s;this.instance=null} function getDocumentFromContext(context){return(window.document)} function getElementAtXpath(xpath){var ps=new ParsedSelector(xpath);var d=getDocumentFromContext(ps.context);return(d.evaluate(ps.path,d,null,XPathResult.ANY_TYPE,null).iterateNext())}} {var el=getElementAtXpath("$return");el.removeAttribute("target");el.setAttribute("download","")}}

scenario jsEval expression
$jsEval= is storeEval on {eval(@expression);}

scenario jsReplace str using subStr and newSubStr
$jsReplace= is storeEval on {"@str".replace(@subStr, "@newSubStr");}

scenario jsSubstr str using start and length
$jsSubstr= is storeEval on {"@str".substr(@start, @length);}

scenario jsSubstring str using indexStart and indexEnd
$jsSubstring= is storeEval on {"@str".substring(@indexStart, @indexEnd);}

scenario jsSlice str using beginSlice and endSlice
$jsSlice= is storeEval on {"@str".slice(@beginSlice, @endSlice);}

scenario jsSplit str using delimeter and index
$jsSplit= is storeEval on {"@str".split("@delimeter")[@index];}

scenario removeCurrency currencyString
$removeCurrency= is storeEval on {function removeCurrency(cs){var ret; ret = cs.replace(/[\$,]/g, ""); return (ret)} removeCurrency("@currencyString")}

scenario display msg
show echo @msg 

NOTE:This scenario is required because of a defect in FitNesse symbol handling. In particular, FitNesse will not evaluate a symbol that is immediately followed by a non-whitespace character. For example, if $XYZ{CODE_END} is a symbol with the value Hello{CODE_END}, then $XYZ World{CODE_END} is evaluated as Hello World{CODE_END}, but $XYZWorld{CODE_END} is evaluated as $XYZWorld{CODE_END}. One might claim that this is expected behavior, accept for the fact that it's not consistent with the evaluation of scenario parameters, which are evaluated correctly whether or not they are followed by whitespace.

scenario concat symbols str1 and str2
$concatSymbols= is storeEval on {"@str1" + "@str2";}

scenario not trueOrFalse
$not= is storeEval on {!@trueOrFalse;}

scenario get seconds timestamp
$getSecondsTimestamp= is storeEval on {Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);}

scenario get today
$getToday= is storeEval on {var date = new Date(); var options = {year: "numeric", month: "2-digit", day: "2-digit"}; new Intl.DateTimeFormat("en-US", options).format(date);}

scenario get today plus days days
$getTodayPlusDays= is storeEval on {Date.prototype.addDays = function(days){var dat = new Date(this.valueOf()); dat.setDate(dat.getDate() + days); return dat;}; var dat = new Date(); var options = {year: "numeric", month: "2-digit", day: "2-digit"}; new Intl.DateTimeFormat("en-US", options).format(dat.addDays(@days));}

scenario get today plus years years
$getTodayPlusYears= is storeEval on {Date.prototype.addYears = function(years){this.setFullYear(this.getFullYear() + years); return this;}; var dat = new Date(); var options = {year: "numeric", month: "2-digit", day: "2-digit"}; new Intl.DateTimeFormat("en-US", options).format(dat.addYears(@years));}

Module commons

Contains module related scenarios that are common to all SUT and client implementations.

  • Expand
  • Collapse

Module



The aliases, declarations, helper methods, and insertion blocks that are used by all modules. For an overview of modules, see Module Overview.

***** Fields *****
These are the aliases that are used when setting the values of individual fields (using the save common. They mimic the actual form field IDs in the SUT and are different for every module. Field aliases are defined within the module itself.

***** Behavior *****
These are the aliases that are used to control the behavior of modules. They are the same for all modules.

Miscellaneous aliases
variable defined: SKIP=%%skip%%

variable defined: SETUP_EMPTY=setupEmpty

variable defined: SETUP_ALL=setupAll

Define graceful versions for pattern/test use:

variable defined: ERROR=${DETECT_ERROR}

variable defined: VERIFY_INVALID=verifyInvalid
Define graceful versions for pattern/test use:
variable defined: VALID=${VERIFY_VALID}
variable defined: INVALID=${VERIFY_INVALID}

Cleanup phase aliases
variable defined: CLEANUP_NONE=cleanupNone
variable defined: CLEANUP_ALL=cleanupAll

Phase: create

During this phase the multistep module is "created" and the behaviors are specified.

scenario MultistepModule.create module
MultistepModule.create @module using setupRequired and openNew and fillRequired and detectError with and verifyValid and cleanupAll

scenario MultistepModule.create module using setupMethod and openMethod and fillMethod and detectMethod with detectParam and verifyMethod and cleanupMethod
MultistepModule.setSetupMethod @module to @setupMethod
MultistepModule.setOpenMethod @module to @openMethod
MultistepModule.setFillMethod @module to @fillMethod
MultistepModule.setDetectMethod @module to @detectMethod
MultistepModule.setDetectParam @module to @detectParam
MultistepModule.setVerifyMethod @module to @verifyMethod
MultistepModule.setCleanupMethod @module to @cleanupMethod

scenario Step.create step with stepContainer
Step.create @step with @{stepContainer} using setupRequired and openNew and fillRequired and submitAndRemain and detectError with and verifyValid and cleanupAll and setupRequired and fillRequired and detectError with and verifyValid

scenario Step.create step with stepContainer using setupMethod and openMethod and fillMethod and submitMethod and detectMethod with detectParam and verifyMethod and cleanupMethod and previousStepSetupMethod and previousStepFillMethod and previousStepDetectMethod with previousStepDetectParam and previousStepVerifyMethod
Module.setSetupMethod @step to @setupMethod
Module.setOpenMethod @step to @openMethod

Module.setSubmitMethod @step to @submitMethod

Module.setDetectParam @step to @detectParam

Module.setCleanupMethod @step to @cleanupMethod

variable defined: COMMON_MULTISTEP_FILL_PHASE= A multistep module container has no fill phase independent of its constituent steps.

Common Validators

These validators greatly simplify the creation of patterns that perform common tests, such as verifying field validation logic and validating an output field for a given set of input fields.

  • Expand
  • Collapse

This validator is designed to validate drop-down labels.

@module.peek
verify dropdown @withSelector has labels @commaSeparatedLabels

Multi-Field Validator

This validator is designed to test field validation logic. Any number of fields can be tested at the same time.

SymbolScenario MultiFieldValidator.create for module
save @module in $multiFieldValidatorActiveModule
@module.create 

IMPORTANT!Why do we split setup and open into two scenarios? The reason is that there are some circumstances where field overrides must be set prior to open. For example, for quote field validation, the customer setup method is called during quote setup, and then the customer runUsing method is called in the quote openNew method. Thus, if we want to override customer fields for a quote, we need to do so before between the setup and open phases. Thus the need to split MultiFieldValidator[?].setup and MultiFieldValidator[?].open.


SymbolScenario MultiFieldValidator.setup
$multiFieldValidatorActiveModule.setup

SymbolScenario MultiFieldValidator.open
$multiFieldValidatorActiveModule.open

scenario MultiFieldValidator.setField fieldAlias to value
save @value in @fieldAlias

SymbolScenario MultiFieldValidator.run detectMethod with detectParam and verifyMethod
$multiFieldValidatorActiveModule.rerunUsing fillAll and submitAndRemain and @detectMethod with @detectParam and @verifyMethod and cleanupNone

SymbolScenario MultiFieldValidator.cleanup
$multiFieldValidatorActiveModule.cleanupAll

  • Collapse

Value Validator

This validator verifies that a field is in a particular state (such as having a specific value). The value validator is very useful for patterns in almost every area of testing.

scenario ValueValidator.verify that field fieldSelector matches regex
save any text in $valueValidatorValue for element @fieldSelector
verify $valueValidatorValue matches @regex

scenario ValueValidator.verify that field fieldSelector equals text
save any text in $valueValidatorValue for element @fieldSelector
verify $valueValidatorValue equals @text

scenario ValueValidator.verify that field fieldSelector is operator to number
save any text in $valueValidatorValue for element @fieldSelector
verify $valueValidatorValue is @operator to @number

@symbol= is storeEval on {function getHiddenValue(selector) {var rawValue = window.document.querySelector(selector).getAttribute('value'); var valueStartIndex = rawValue.indexOf('OriginalValue=') + 14; var valueEndIndex = rawValue.indexOf('|', valueStartIndex); return (rawValue.substring(valueStartIndex, valueEndIndex));} try{getHiddenValue('@withSelector');}catch(e){};}

IMPORTANT! From IIC AFTs: Wait for the job to Complete (make sure timeout is set properly so it has enough time). The wait when selecting the refresh interval is to help ensure the test doesn't try to click the return button while the page is still refreshing from the select. This can happen if the job is so fast that its status is completed the first time the job history page displays.

set step delay to 500

set step delay to 0
wait for page to load

Set test teardown behavior

NOTE:Default to keeping browser open when test ends. Can be overridden within inidvidual tests.

IMPORTANT!The following script table, along with the corresponding TEST_PAGE_END script table, can not be moved into the FitNesse SuiteSetUp[?]/SuiteTearDown pages. The reason is that while symbols have global scope{—}meaning they are available to all suites/tests in the current execution context{—}this does not seem to include the SuiteSetUp[?]/SuiteTearDown pages. I have tested this thoroughly, and it seems that symbols that are created within tests (or even in SuiteSetup[?]) are not available in the SuiteTeardown[?] page. Surprisingly, even variables that are created in tests or SuiteSetup[?] are not available in SuiteTearDown[?].  Thus, these script tables must appear within the test itself.


SymbolScript
keep browser open when test ends
scenario keep browser open when test ends
save keepBrowserOpen in $testTeardownMethod
scenario save this in that
$testTeardownMethod<-[keepBrowserOpen] echo keepBrowserOpen

scenario click any element withSelector
toJsSelector #Menu_Policy_NewCustomerAndQuote

teardown test

NOTE:Run the teardown method for this test. The teardown method is set using the scenarios keep browser open when test ends and close browser when test ends.


NOTE:For backwards compatibility with SutLoginProfileSet[?] pages that don't support SUT_LOGIN_METHOD/SUT_LOGOUT_METHOD, we need to provide a default value for those symbols. Unfortunately, we need to start by "reincluding" the SutLoginProfileSet[?] page because, while it was previously included in the SuiteSetUp[?] context, FitNesse does not allow test pages to access the SuiteSetUp[?] context
